💫 #BTS Harmony* Brand Shoot with @sarahezrinyoga💫

Sarah was my yoga teacher when I went through yoga teacher training. Then, she became one of my first photography clients. Over time, we became friends as we bonded over living in LA and all things wellness (aka stretchy pants 💁🏼‍♀️💁🏻‍♀️).

To work with her on this re-brand was such a full circle moment. Such an honor to be called in for this project and to see how far she has come, now a mama to two boys and about to launch her new book (pre-orders available!!!).

I’m so proud of her for stepping into this stage in life with confidence, grace and strength. She called in @krystenleighmay for styling help, @oliviagarvinmakeup for hair and make up and rented this gorgeous @peerspace in Petaluma.

I’d laugh but then I start coughing 

I was at the pediatrician’s office FOUR TIMES in the past week.

I told them they need to start giving parent’s punchcards so every 10th visit is free.

It is laughable, but it’s also terrifying. This wintergedon of RSV and HFM and every other acronym my son’s preschool has introduced me to, has been intense.

This isn’t just about kids getting sick or ending up in the hospital, either. It’s about the lack of systems in place to support American families in these times. Like no sick days (google rail workers strike) or affordable childcare.

Things are fracturing beneath us and we’re being swallowed whole. All I can do is reach out my hand to other parents going through the same thing and hope we can laugh about it together, when it doesn’t make us cough so much.

Loving reminder to postpartum parents, but really anyone who has lungs and a torso…

Your belly is meant to expand when you take an inhale. It is not only normal, but healthy.

“Sucking our stomachs in” or even wearing close that constrict the belly (like corsets in the old days) can wreak havoc on the life giving systems of our body. Not only does holding in your tummy all day mess with you getting a full breath (which might then lead to anxiety), but your digestive system may get messed up too.

No more holding in your tummy, plz! Someone thinks you still look preggers? Good! Say, “im pregnant with self-love” or “im pregnant with breath.”

Love you all

Xo

But it’s not just the energy boost I love about caffeine. 

I love the ritual. I love the taste of warm sweetened beverages, and the feeling of a hot cup in my hand. Especially in the winter (though post kids it’s more like a luke warm cup).

What inspired me to write The Yoga of Parenting? Have you ever spent the morn with 2 young kids?

It can be a whole lot of OMGs SMHs FFSs. It can be a whole lot of reacting.

I wrote this book because I was tired of beating myself up after every blunder. I was tired of always trying to make moments perfect and in doing so, missing them entirely. I was tired of feeling the need to orchestrate what my entire family was doing all the time (and neglecting my own needs in the process).

So I went to my teachers: other parents, texts, and studies, and I discovered something pretty cool. All of the lessons I learn every day on my mat and in my meditation can be applied to my parenting.

All the answers I sought, all the tools I needed, I had them all along, bc they are inside of me. Just as every thing you need is inside of YOU. Only we know our children best.

Did I write this book to help you become a better parent??? No, I wrote this book to remind us that we already are.

TW su1€ide
My brother took his own life in 2008. 

Last week would have been his 56th birthday. It was also the date he chose to leave this world; to leave his pain behind.

When someone we know well (or know of well) does this, it is often unfathomable. 

Everyone suddenly starts questioning their part. 

What could I have done differently?

We post things like, “check on your friends” and the number to hotlines. And we feel a little bit better.

We say things like, “su1€ide is selfish.” We use anger to dampen our grief.

But even in this desperate attempt to understand we have missed the point.

Bc it was never about us. 

Could we consider that some people’s pain is just so great this is their chosen path to freedom? Is that selfish?

Someone asked me how much yoga I’m doing these days and I sheepishly said, “not much!.”

Me. The one who wrote a whole book called The Yoga of Parenting hoping to remind yoga practitioner parents everywhere that yoga is not just asana.

Me. The one will is always the very first to clap back on someone’s comment when they say they aren’t doing much yoga, yet I see them raising children.

What is the saying? The shoe makers children have no shoes?

I was feeling sooo guilty that I hadn’t had a chance to move my body yet today, but when I took a deep breath (my first deep breath of the day probs), I remembered: PARENTING IS YOGA.

And when I think about it like that, then I see that I have been doing yoga allllll morning.

Which means you can and prob are to.

In fact, let’s do something together right now: STOP whatever you’re doing and simply breathe.
Inhale, pause. Exhale, pause.
*PS if breathing is inaccessible or triggering, then simply feel your foundation (or whatever is on the floor).

Now, face that toddler tantrum. That’s advanced yoga my loves.

I will never forget when I got mad and someone said to me, “um don’t you do yoga?!”

Even my own dad will sometimes gently suggest I “use my yoga” when I’m feeling highly anxious or upset about something.

Spoiler alert! 🚨 It’s not unyogic to feel anger (or sadness or worry or any of the other uncomfortable emotions we deem “negative”).

In fact, yoga is the practice of sitting in that discomfort and learning how to harness it for power. To alchemist it, if you will.

Anger breeds action and activism. Sadness is a release and cleanse. Worry is an evolutionary red flag. 

It’s not unyogic to feel these things, so yes, even yoga teachers get mad. And ESPECIALLY yoga teachers who are also parents or caretakers bc kids are stressful.

The yoga for me today was not NOT getting angry, I think it was in the managing my emotions to use them most effectively. 

✖️ It was probs not effective to snap at my hubs this morn (sorry Ben!)
✔️ It was effective for me to use my anger as fuel to get me moving at a speed that was necessary to get me to class on time. 
✖️ It was not effective for me to rush my already flustered toddler 
✔️ It was effective to use that moment for both of us to ground and breathe 

🙋🏻‍♀️Your turn: have you ever harnessed your anger for something positive?! Share below 👇🏼

Sing it w/ me: it’s the most stressful time of the year.🎵🎼 oh oops, I meant wonderful…right????

The holidays also happen to be a time that many of us think we don’t have any time to do yoga.

Well good news 👏🏻 yoga isn’t just poses. It’s sooo many other amazing practices that I bet you are already doing!

Here’s 3 yoga-informed tips for staying grounded this season:

1️⃣Breathe- yup, seems simple, but it’s not. Right now, stop reading, scrolling, cooking whatever and just take a deep BREATH

2️⃣ Move your body: “Wait, didn’t you just say yoga isn’t poses?”. Movement is anything that puts your bod in motion. 👋🏼

3️⃣ Boundaries, baby. Say “no” and say it often. PS you are not responsible for other’s feelings about the choices you need to make to support yourself.

The more connected we are with our self, the more connected we will be with our family.

I look at my tummy and think “ugh” but I look at my baby’s tummy and think “ahh.” 

Where’s the disconnect????

Why do we love a baby’s rolls but shame the mom when they have them too?

I’ve been trying to remind myself, every time I have a negative thought about my body to focus on something I’m grateful for about that part. 

I’ve been thanking my stomach for digesting the food that fuels me and for making room for my womb to house my two sons. I’ve been thanking my face (my wrinkles) for stretching to allow me to laugh and smile.

We see our children with nonjudgmental eyes, but then turn around and look at ourselves in disgust.

What would it feel like to see yourself with the same awe, wonder, and gratitude that you look at a baby?

✨ I want you to try something for me: Pick the part of yourself that you are hardest on and in the comments share one thing about that area that you’re grateful for👇🏼

TW food, body, and the holidays🚨

“Wow, you’re going back for more?!” 

“You ate that whole plate?!”

“Are you suuuure you want to eat that?”

Family members have a tendency to overstep their boundaries during the holidays when it comes to talking about people’s bodies and food consumption.

Thankfully the old approach of, “just be nice! they’re family” is as antiquated as that platter you’re fam has been using for generations. In fact is kind of the same thing. Old relics of the past that we can toss away.

You can be the change. You can ask for change. You can set a boundary of what is appropriate and what you are willing to tolerate.

You do not have to “be nice” at the expense of your sanity and mental health.

All that’s easier said than done, so here are 3 effective tips that I have personally used when dealing with fam members commenting on my weight or food:

🔹 Breathing before I set the boundary that I don’t want to discuss my food or body. 

🔹Choosing to not engage.

🔹Powering up on self-touch and affirmations✨

We cannot control what other people are going to say or do. We can only control our reactions. 

Try to remember just how perfect and amazing you are. Our bodies are going to change. But the essence of who you are—that perfection—that is eternal.
✨✨✨

Good luck out there these next few weeks. Love you all.

Xo

There’s a natural come down day after any big event (holiday, bdays, vacations). 

Think about how long you are looking forward to some things and then how quickly it can be over.

In the case of Christmas, we prepare for a month or more and then boom it’s done.

This “come down” is a form of grief and can feel like mourning for our little ones. There is a loss of the build up, a loss of the family gathering, a loss of the high. 

A lot of us try to brush these periods over through over scheduling or high emotional expectations.

We can teach our kids to honor this natural come down day by talking about it with them beforehand and then letting them lead when they’re in it.

No one likes that low feeling after such a high, but we can help them understand that the high is so high bc of these rest periods.

Q FOR YOU: Do you talk to your kid about the “come down”? What do you say?

The struggle is real. But did you know it doesn’t have to be a struggle?

Comedowns are inevitable outcomes of highs, especially the day after Xmas. We spend a month (sometimes more) preparing for this singular day. 

Yes, it’s the Christmas “season,” but ultimately it culminates to one or two days, which means they end. 

Sure, there’s all year Christmas options, but is it really as special if you celebrate every day?

It’s the fleetingness of it that is precisely what makes it so precious.

Thankfully yoga can guide us on how to handle these comedowns consciously:

1. Anticipate it: You will land a little more softly when you see the drop off ahead.

2. Honor what you’re feeling. Want to sleep? Sleep. Want to veg? Veg. 

3. Embrace it: Remind yourself that the lows are necessary counterparts to the highs. 

This is often deemed a weird week bc of the low we feel, but what if this week is exactly the lull it needs to be so we can begin the #newyear on a high?

Presence is a muscle that has atrophied for a lot of us.

Even though many neurotypical kids are born with well-developed presence muscles (is there any one more present than a baby?!) that muscle tends to weaken over time. 

We can help our kids continue to strengthen their presence muscles and in the process, rebuild ours as well.

3 tips for ENCOURAGING mindfulness:

1️⃣ Snack in “stillness” 
* Pro-tip: this doesn’t mean they cant move their bodies, but rather set aside the space and time to focus on snacking instead of snacking on the go 

2️⃣ Breath before action
*Pro tip: Make this fun by using animals sounds or visualization to encourage deeper breathing 

3️⃣ Let them lead and try not to rush them
*Not recommended when you’re in a rush

The truth is, it is our kids who will help US strengthen our presence muscles. 

🤷🏻‍♀️Q4U: What are ways you weave mindfulness into your parenting?

Self-care is self-preservation, even (and perhaps especially?) for moms.

Moms/dads/caretakers of all kind are known for giving, but we forget that in order to give we must also receive. It’s not just lip service to say we must put our own oxygen mask on first.

If there is an emergency and we’re not taken care, who will take care of everyone else?

Yet most of us let our needs fall way down the priority list. We give until we’re empty; until we’re out of air.

I’ve started to do simple self-care actions every day to fill my tank a little. They also happen to help me feel like Sarah vs just mom.

3 things I do:
• Unapologetic hygiene: you should not need permission to wash your face or go to the bathroom. Is there better times? Yes, but you declare your needs and then figure out how to get them 

• Putting on a little bit of make up. 
Look I’m a pretty natural gal. Mostly out of impatience, but a little makeup goes a long way for sense of self.
• Getting dressed in real clothes
*I get paid to wear yoga pants. Not literally, but you know what I mean. So wearing jeans that fits, just helps me feel like a real person.

🤷🏻‍♀️Q4U: What’s one thing you can do for yourself today to fill your tank?

Forget your highlight reel, give me your REAL reel.

I’m feeling incredibly inspired by @thefifthtrimester and her friends for keeping their 2022 round ups REAL by sharing lowlights in addition to the highlights.

I’m even going to add in a third category of my own: “mid-lights”, which were quiet, uneventful moments.

Every single experience we go through is a thread weaving together the beautiful tapestry of our life. 

We label things positive, negative, or neutral, but when we pull back and see the big picture that is our life, we understand that every thread was necessary to make the whole picture. 

Even the ones that felt like mistakes or we were certain would lead to knots. It is often especially these “mistakes” that make our lives so beautiful.

Highlights 
🌟Welcoming my second son into the world 
🌟Finishing my first book!!!
🌟Leading my first Yoga of Parenting workshop 
🌟So.much.family.
🌟Rebranding my business to include this new official role of author and mama of two. (Love you @emilie.bers) 

Lowlights
✅ HG pregnancy 
✅ Getting a cold with HG pregnancy 
✅ Getting stomach flu with HG pregnancy
✅ The cost of childcare for two children 
✅ Navigating the changing family dynamics of having two children 

Midlights
🔹The full time job that is breastfeeding 
🔹Napping with the baby
🔹Family dinners
🔹Sunsets with my toddler 
🔹Quiet mornings to write and meditate 

👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼Your turn…Share a little bit of it all plz, because it ALL matters. The good, the bad, the neutral—they’re are all parts of you.🫶🏻

I would define boundaries as knowing where you end and someone else begins.

And a huge component for me is the willingness and ability to sit in the discomfort of another’s disappointment or disapproval.

I want to take care of everyone, all the times. 

That random gal in the market who answered the Q you were actually asking the store clerk? That’s me.🙋🏻‍♀️

While it’s a wonderful trait (and it is), it is not always selfless. A huge motivator is often not wanting someone to be upset, especially when it comes to the possibility of someone being upset with ME.

So while taking you to aisle 5 to find those almonds seemed like my good deed for the day, it was also me being totally unable to sit there knowing you were lost and needed help. 

Okay, maybe that’s not the cleanest example. 

How about: Saying yes to something when we can’t or don’t want to, going out of your way to please another person at the expense of your own happiness.

Ring any bells???🛎️ 

When I can sit with another’s disappointment and be clear that I am here and they are there and I am making the right decision for me in this moment, I actually feel even better and have even more energy and selfless love to give than had I done something inauthentic.

🤷🏻‍♀️Q4U: how would you define boundaries? What is your experience with disappointing others?

A lot of us have self-care all wrong.

We assume .it has to be overt and luxurious, like spending the day at the spa. 

But then when we do finally take that weekend getaway or sleep in, it doesn’t really seem to move the needle when it comes to our exhaustion, and often times we feel robbed. 

A few simple mindset shifts can help us learn how to practice self-care more sustainably and effectively!

1️⃣ Self-care doesn’t have to be luxurious or event overt. Attitude shifts and boundary setting count. 

2️⃣Self-care should be something that we do a little bit of everyday. 

It’s like taking little sips of water throughout the day versus chugging a gallon once a week and expecting not to feel dehydrated.

3️⃣ Be unapologetic about meeting your basic needs. **THAT is the self-care in the hygiene equation…

Though you can also consider adding in a little extra flair to level up, like using special shampoo, or doing a mask.

Self-care is not selfish. It’s self-preservation. If you don’t give to yourself you will have nothing to give.

What do you see? Bc I guarantee it’s different than what I see.

A lot of energy and time went into this photo shoot. I’d been planning it since before I even wrote my book The Yoga of Parenting.

For real. I reached out @emilie.bers and asked her to do the marketing photos right when my proposal got accepted.

In my head, I was so excited to get the “perfect shot”. My friend and the writer of my book’s foreword @jenpastiloff had these AMAZING images she used to market her book On Being Human and I remember thinking, “THAT! I want that!”

But when the day of my shoot arrived, I had to curb my original visions.

First, I was convinced that I’d be back to my pre baby body, so I scheduled it for 6mo postpartum. 

I also thought that could guarantee that my baby would be sitting, maybe even crawling and we could get some epic photo of them running around me.

That’s not what happened. I def had not lost the baby weight (still haven’t 3 mo later) and Jacob still can’t sit on his own.

When I got the shots, all I could see is what didn’t go “right.” Most notably my body…

What’s funny though is that even though the baby didn’t do what I expected, I wasn’t mad at him or disappointed with the outcome.

I laughed every time he toppled over. I think he looks even cuter in some ways.

It’s the messiness of the picture that I love the most and when I started to embrace myself with the same non judgment and unconditional love I embrace my children with, I fell in love with the photo.

I realized that everything needed to be exactly as it was (my #postpartumbody included) in order to capture this moment.

And now when I see it, my mind goes to just how perfectly imperfect it is.

Parenthood can be messy and overwhelming. 

But I think a large part of why that happens is because our “stuff” gets sprinkled all over whatever stressor is occurring in the moment…which tends to make things even more challenging than it already was.

Sooo let’s say a toddler (not mine off bc mine is an 👼🏻 and would never do such things *said with exceeding sarcasm), but “someone’s” toddler is jumping on the dining room chair during dinner after you asked them to stop. 

Before you’ve even had a second to think, you’re mentally catapulted back to when you were a little kid doing something upsetting at the dinner table and how your parents reacted.

Just as quickly you’re mentally catapulted wayyyyy forward, picturing your child being kicked out of college for not following the rules.

By the time all of these parts of you come back to the present moment, where your kid is still jumping on the chair, you’ve completely lost your ground (and by ground I mean sh*t).

Yoga is a practice of slowing everything down so we start to see what is real.

It helps us recognize, “oh that’s a past trigger arising” or “that’s a future projection” or “do I even really care that they’re jumping on this chair or is that society” 

And suddenly this seemingly silly incident of your kid jumping on a chair becomes a deep dive into YOU.

Suddenly, this moment that felt overwhelming and messy is actually an amazing opportunity to get to know yourself and maybe even heal.

Our kids can be amazing yoga teachers and parenting is yoga.

Regressions? Tantrums? Lying? Screaming? Parenthood has a lot of storms.

It’s been raining for weeks here in the Bay. It can be hard to remember what sunny days are like sometimes, but even though the storm seems unrelenting, we know in our gut that the sun will return. 

This is the truth of nature. Things are constantly changing.

Stormy periods of parenthood are not dissimilar. 

Whether it’s a sleep regression or tantrum or our kid is going through a tough time socially at school, our brain can question if the period will ever end. and even if we know it’s all temporary, the time we’re in it can feel interminable.

Yoga can provide a life raft during these storm periods. It’s no ocean liner, I assure you. 

We will still get knocked around and flipped upside down at times, but the practice can give us an opportunity to stay afloat. Or at the very least, climb our way back out of the waves.

Here’s 3 tips to stay afloat the next storm
✅ Look to nature to remember everything is temporary.
✅ Recall other storms you have weathered.
✅ Allow ALL the feels.

⚠️ Intrusive thoughts 
Everything is going really well right now, so naturally my anxiety is THROUGH the roof.

I can’t seem to settle into the calm. I’m feel like I’m just awaiting the next crisis life will inevitably bring (because life is a series of ups and downs and no amount of worrying can prevent that).

I’m checking my phone constantly, panicked by every phone call, gritting my teeth, welling up in tears without warning.

When these moments arise I try to do everything I can to bring myself back to the present reality. To remind myself that right now, in this moment, everything truly is okay. And that it’s okay that it’s okay.

Today, I ran my hand under freezing water when I had a thought of something bad happening to my son. Yesterday I practiced the mantra, “we are all healthy, we are all healthy.”

None of these are magic fixes but they help hold that scared little girl inside of me and bring her back to the now, where everything really is okay. 

Everyone really is healthy today. And she (me), we are safe.

🤷🏻‍♀️Q4U: what do you do when you’re feeling anxious during a joyous or neutral time? What is the most effective practice to bring you back to the moment?

#intrusivethoughts seems to be trending on social these days.

I’m grateful to all the people willing to help shine a light on how wild our mind can get, especially for new parents!!!

When my oldest was born, I had an overwhelming feeling that something bad was going to happen. 

I constantly checked to make sure he was breathing at night and couldn’t say goodbye without ceremony. 

You will hear a lot of yoga teachers say “you can choose your thoughts”!

Some even refer to the practice as mind control.

But let me tell you, I was not controlling anything those early days. 

My thoughts were controlling me. 

I’d be frozen, overwhelmed in parking lots unable to enter stores. I couldn’t close my eyes, lest I see horrifying images.

Here I was a yoga teacher, and yet I couldn’t do the simple thing that we all swear yoga teaches us to do.

Move over #momguilt , yoga teacher guilt is no joke. 

I felt like I was failing at being a mom AND a yoga teacher.

Things got worse before they got better, but they did get better. I sought professional treatment and I started to take back my mind and that’s when I realized: This idea that you can always choose your thoughts is BS.

Intrusive thoughts are just that: intrusive. We don’t and cannot always choose them.

But we CAN always try to choose the thought that comes after. When we have the right support.

Spoiler alert: meditating as a parent will NOT look like it did prior to kids.

I mean maybe you get lucky one day and get a whole 30min. Or maybe your kids have grown up and are out of the house.

But for parents of young kids, it’s likely your sits and practices have been much shorter, messier, and even broken up. 

It can feel impossible to get time to do nothing, when you are taking care of so many people.

We know intellectually that or quiet time (I think @neeti.narula calls this “think time”) will make you a better parent, but how do we find the time to do it?!

Here are 3 tips to finding time to meditate as a busy parent:
1️⃣ Try to wake up before everyone. I know this is challenging. I’ve been getting up at 430a and Jacob is on to me, but even if you can give yourself 15 min before the madness, it’s worth it!!!
2️⃣ Readjust your time expectations. 10-15 min a day makes a difference!!! Even a number of 2min sits sprinkled over a few hours will have an impact
3️⃣Meditation doesn’t mean sitting in silence. Get creative. Discover what things make you feel “in flow”, and then do those often

I think the most important thing is that you take time just for you, so you have more of you to give.

Q4U🤷🏻‍♀️ how do you find time to meditate on busy days?

PS Um also this is very much a filter 🙄

Sorry @bigtimeadulting , I’m one of those annoying morning meditation moms, BUT I promise it’s not what it looks like!

A big reason I get up at 430a is because I never really went back to sleep after my second baby started sleeping longer stretches…

I still wake up most nights at 12a, 3, and 430a and one day I thought, F- it, I’m going to take advantage of this time! I’m a huge introvert and need alone time and if it takes a 430a wake up, let’s do this!

Now, my youngest somehow smells me and wakes up too on most days, but I’ve been able to do at least 10-15min of meditation and OMG am I a better mom/wife/person?!

Does this mean you have to start getting up early and meditating, too? NO! Absolutely not!!!

Everyone needs different things to thrive. Maybe you’re a night owl? Maybe you’re more focused in motion? Maybe you are better hiding in the Starbucks parking lot 🤷🏻‍♀️

The questions aren’t how early you can get up or how long you can sit quietly for. The question is: what’s YOUR one non-negotiable, that you need to try to do EVERY day to feel like a whole you?

“Trusting her children was another fundamental difference with Dianne’s upbringing. But trust goes hand in hand with empowerment. If she gave her sons freedom, then she had to trust they would make the right choices. Hence, her favorite phrase became (and still is) ‘Make good choices.’

I hate swimming.

My husband and eldest son love it. Like, LOVE.

They go often and naturally, because they love it so much, they want to share it with me.

But I really don’t like swimming.

Worth mentioning is that when they go swimming, I then get to do something for “me” (my baby is usually strapped to me, but I choose our activities).

One day, they begged me to come swimming and I felt sooo guilty for not wanting to come.

How dare I do what I wanted to do instead? I heard society call me “selfish.” I felt my husband and son’s disappointment in my bones.

So even though I knew on that day that I needed to do my own thing and that I hate swimming, I went….and you know what???

I still hated it. 

And I realized: I wasn’t doing anyone any favors by ignoring ny inner needs. If anything, I soured THEIR swim bc I was so uncomfy.

I don’t need to do and love everything they do. There are plenty of things we do as a family or that I do alone with my kids. 

I can skip swimming and still be a decent mom.

I can hate swimming and still be a good mom.

I can choose myself and still be a great mom.

Psst want to know a secret 🤫 Yoga teachers yell at their kids.

Real talk: You will NEVER bounce back. The fitness industry is lying to you.

It is physiologically impossible. Our body replaces billions of cells per day and research shows that even if a person is pregnant for just a few weeks their genetic code changes as it absorbs baby’s cells.

Look, maybe you will get your weight back where it was, maybe your clothes will fit. Maybe you will even look the same on the outside.

But inside, you will NEVER bounce back because motherhood and pregnancy altar your very DNA.

And that’s a beautiful thing.

What if we stopped spending all of our energy trying to get back to who we were? 

Because it is an impossible endeavor, one we are guaranteed to fail.

What if instead we worked on accepting and embracing the new us?

What if the reason you don’t recognize who you see in the mirror is NOT because you need to get back to who you once were, but because you should be getting to know yourself as you are now?

Because from where I stand you are fierce and you are beautiful.

I’m also not going to stop bringing awareness to gaping issues like the need for paid family leave, affordable healthcare and maternal health resources.

The word that comes to mind when I read @octaviaraheem ‘s work is ‘permission’.
 It was for that reason that when my editor @bethfrankl and I were thinking of people to read and review my book early, Octavia came to mind immediately. 

I had been following her teachings for some time before reading her book Pause, Rest, Be, and her book became a permission slip for me to just rest during a super tough pregnancy.

I cried when I read her testimonial for my book. It was so beautiful and I am so honored.

There’s no overt correlation between restorative practices and Black History Month. But maybe there should be. 

I just know that as a Black woman, I’m tired. And my inner Superwoman didn’t want to say that out loud.

I’m tired of watching news story after news story of people whose skin—brown like mine—caused them to be mistreated, harmed, and killed by accident and on purpose.

I’m tired of doing everything I can to create some sense of inner stability in a society that often turns to Black folks for the innovation, the labor, and the education on how to do better. 

I’m tired of trying to do the most in order to find financial security to bring  ease to my body.

I’m tired of the expectation of toil. 

Tracee Stanley @tracee_stanley asked the question: Who modeled rest for you? And I realized the answer was NO ONE.  I have never had anything other than hard work modeled for me—hard work in a playing field where the right to security, comfort, and rest have never been level.

Read more from my article in @yogajournal about the importance of rest BECAUSE YOU CAN, and because health outcomes are directly related to it. I discuss Dr. Gail Parker’s @drgailparker research about resting as a balm to racial wounding, and how to integrate rest into your day. 

While I hope that this article inspires respite and respect for rest in all, my hope is that my fellow BIPOC folks, who have been tasked over centuries to carry a disproportionate amount of toil, will disrupt the culture of overwork that is literally killing us earlier than others.

Parents: How do you feel when you’re with your kids and your mind wanders?

If you’re anything like me, you probably spend the next 30min beating yourself up, only to miss being present with them once again.

I think there’s a misconception that yoga is about being present every second of every day. But we’re human beings, our minds wander.

The practice is much less about being physically present 24/7 and so much more about strengthening our awareness for when our mind’s inevitably wander.

And a wandering mind isn’t always a bad thing, it’s where I juice up creatively and where I work things out.

My mind wanders a lot when I’m with my kids. I can’t get that time I zoned out back, but I can always decide what I do next and I’d much rather focus my energy on being present with them NOW then beating myself up for not being present 10min ago.

Q4U🤷🏻‍♀️ What’s the best tool you have for getting present with your kids again when your mind has wandered?

I still can’t figure out what I forgot today, but im pretty sure I forgot something.

This morning was madness. 

Feeding two demanding crying kids, dressing two demanding crying kids.

Then trying to get everyone out the door on time, while also dealing with the cleaners (I want to be transparent about this privilege as it’s one way I’ve made my village).

At one point there was 7 people in my kitchen, and a needy dog.

This wasn’t a unique situation either (well, the cleaners aren’t there every day, but you know I mean), this is breakfast.

Parenting is high stress and it takes every single tool I’ve ever learned in my 41yrs of life to navigate the chaos.

Here are 3 of the tools that worked best for me today:
▶️ Breathing— both with my toddler when he was starting to have a meltdown and by myself when I was going to have one.

▶️ Becoming a stealth observer—not unlike when we try to become the seer in meditation, I try to pull back from the situation and see it from the outside.

▶️ Putting my phone away—friends and work can wait in those moments. Even just turning it face down is helpful.

Q4U🤷🏻‍♀️What are the most effective tools you use in chaotic parenting moments?

Who decided men look more distinguished with age and women get uglier?

I’ve found myself pouring an obscene amount of time (and money) into my skin care lately.

Part of it is self-care but there’s another part that is trying to slow the inevitable process of aging.

My products all have some “anti-aging” quality or synonym in their title.

I’m doing new skin care trends that I see on TikTok and it’s fucking exhausting.

Who decided that beauty has to be this much work? Who decided that beauty was the goal? And who decides what is beautiful?

I’ve decided that I’m going to take all that energy and money and channel it into self-love.

I’m not going to stop my eye patches or masks because they feel good. Or my long nighttime routine bc it’s a moment of peace.

But I am going to stop buying every products with the intention that it will help me look younger and less tired, bc the reality is: I’m 41 and I’m tired. 

The time I spend looking in the mirror will be a time for grieving and celebrating, but it will no longer be a time where I criticize or judge myself.

Nope. Not going to do it. Good luck IG targeting see if I buy another wrinkle reducing cream off here again 😂

Here are 2 things I do when I need to ask for help as a hyperindependent mom:
▶️ I convince myself the person will be mad at me if I do ask.
▶️ I get mad at that person before they’ve even had a chance to reject me and do it myself.

In other words, asking for help is very hard for me.

I knew that the scared part of me was my little girl self who had to walk on eggshells and who often felt like a burden (though also deeply loved). 

And I always assumed the “F u I got this” was the response to that little girl self. The protector, but what I just realized this morn is that the “FU I got this” side is actually my teenage self!!!! 

And it’s not a protective response! It’s a fear response!!!!!!

Ok, mind BLOWN.

Now, the work is channeling my adult self to remind both of those parts that we are safe. We are OK and we are worth it.

My kids don’t define me, but they sure helped me get clear on who I truly am.

A lot of my initial resistance to having a family was around a fear of loss. 

I had a fear of losing them, but I was/am equally afraid of losing myself.

I work really hard every day to maintain my sense of self in motherhood—even when my needs may conflict with my children or my husband.

It’s not easy and not everyone in my family gets it, but I do. I get it.

Becoming a mother has forced me to get super clear on who I am and what I need.

Am I ALL mom ALL the time? No. It’s a huge part of me, but I am so much more, and fighting to maintain those separate aspects of self has actually helped me define them. 

I love my children more than words can express. I am so glad I am a mom. But I am also still Sarah.

Motherhood is not where I am going to lose myself, it is a path to my truest self.

I had a major scare today with both boys.

I fell while holding the baby, then the toddler tripped over us and face-planted. 

Lots of blood, thankfully no concussions, but man,
my nervous system is WRECKED.

The boys are both thankfully totally okay, my lower back is TBD, but I keep replaying the incident over and over again. I keep hearing certain sounds, seeing certain images.

In the past I would’ve poured myself into work. I would’ve been equally anxious about missing appointments and rescheduling everything as soon as the kids were napping.

But today, I did it differently.

I had to, because my boys were watching me. They were scared and they needed to regulate too.

So I let them stay home and we have stayed quiet all day (I mean other than shooting a rocket launcher in the backyard). 

But the most nourishing thing I’ve done so far, since I can’t really bust into a restorative pose or take a nap while watching my baby, is take him to the water and get low to the ground.

I immediately felt better and I think he did too. 

If you’ve had a big scare or upset recently and you have a tendency to plow ahead, I invite you to try something different.

Get outside. Get low and get still.

I recently posted about fatigue with always “having to do.”

A few friends rightly suggested switching my “I have to do’s” with “I get to do” and while that is a lovely sentiment, and I appreciate where they’re coming from (srsly no shade) as an overworked, under-supported mother living in the US, I’m not sure that is the best solution for me.

Telling moms to just view all the mundane childrearing tasks that invade our mental space and suck our precious energy and time as a privilege (bc imagine if we didn’t have kids or something worse, heaven forbid) is actually the equivalent of putting a balm all over a gaping wound and hoping it will heal.

In this case, the balm is toxic positivity, hence my new fave phrase “toxic positivity balm.”

As with most things in life, it’s a yes/and. 

Yes, we can acknowledge that it’s a privilege to be mothers AND that shit is EXHAUSTING.

Some things that could help heal the wound of the overworked, under-supported American mother would be:
✅ Offering to help in some way *bonus points if you’re specific on what you can do 
✅ Mirroring a mom’s fatigue and frustration 
✅ Vote for lawmakers who support childcare initiatives and family policy 
✅ Support organizations like @chamberofmothers who work hard to effect policy change 

Gratitude is absolutely a medicine and it is very helpful for healing, but it is not a magic pill. It’s just a temporary, soothing balm on the gaping wound that is American motherhood.

I haven’t come to my mat in days. I haven’t even really moved my body, other than to hold my sick baby in my arms and rub his back. 

Thankfully, his 3 day fever turned out to “only” be an ear infection, but he has wanted nothing more than to be lying next to me on my b00b with my attention entirely on him.

I’ve had to cancel work commitments two days in a row and I can’t help feeling like people will never forgive me. But then I come back to my purpose in this moment and I’m reminded of what really matters: him- THAT is yoga.

I observe my mind (and google search) travel to some very dark spaces, before we had answers and I I only had a listless baby burning up my arms. But I used my body and his touch to anchor back to now where he is here and safe- THAT is yoga.

I watched myself holding my breath yesterday afternoon as he wailed, unable to be soothed, while my toddler also yelled for my attention. I took a deep breath and was able to attend to them as fast as I could, even though the other wasn’t pleased- THAT is yoga.

It doesn’t mean I don’t feel guilty for not moving my body, or that I don’t need a good Downward Facing Dog, but for now I will remind myself, to stop saying “I haven’t done yoga today” bc parenting IS yoga.

It’s easy to look at my body and only see it’s flaws. I get obsessed over which thigh is bigger and which hair is out of place. I pull at my tummy like taffy and try to beat it back in.

I all but take a measuring stick to my eyebrows and hair. There’s so much pressure to make everything just so.

But when I look at my kids, they’re just perfect. Their little mismatched eyebrows and crooked teeth.
Their Buddha-round tummies and dimpled knuckles.
I see nothing but perfection, even and especially when things are totally misaligned!

And do you know how they see me? Well, they definitely aren’t thinking about my one b00b being 3x the size of its pair (okay, maybe Jacob does think about that 😂🍼🥛). Or how my bunions have grown or how I can’t wear yoga pants without them rolling.

To them my body is a playground. It’s a pillow and a blanket, a shelter and an island. To them, my body is perfect, because to them, my body is home. 

I write about learning to embrace our  asymmetries in @yogajournal this week. @drmalekpt and @pyogalab both share some beautiful advice.

We are all perfectly imperfect and that’s what makes us all special.

“@nishthef1sh is not only a TikTok sensation and guitar player but also a lifelong student of Vedanta philosophy and Tantra. 

He grew up in his grandfather’s ashram in Sri Lanka, memorizing texts before he even knew what the words meant. 

He made the move at 17 years old to come to the US and study at the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA).

Selvalingam suggests that parents may want to take a more Tantric approach to tapas. Where many modern teachers and literary interpretations explain tapas as “challenges leading to transformation,” Selvalingam jokes that transformation and growth are actually considered bad words in the Tantra lineage. 

Instead, Tantrikas, like Nish, see tapas as a method of purification. Meaning that the intense fire that we face is not to change who we are but to burn away that which we are not. 

As Nish says, ‘Our work is not actually to grow or to heal. The work is to recognize the perfection that is already there.’ “ excerpted from The Yoga of Parenting, Chapter 5 When Challenges Become Gifts.

“I used to think yoga was one-size-fits-all and that everyone would respond in the same way if “prescribed” a certain pose. 

Feeling low on energy? Try a dynamic Sun Salutation. Want to open your heart? Do some backbends.

After teaching thousands upon thousands of people over the past fifteen years and observing my own body (and life) change every day, I have learned that yoga is not nearly that black and white. 

It’s not even gray. 

I think of it as shades of neutral with some purple and pink hues.

Some of yoga’s potency–the “medicinal” quality of the practice—comes from you, the practitioner. It can depend on the intention behind the poses. Which means that, depending on how you feel on a given day, you can curate a sequence to serve exactly what you need. Like a true alchemist.

Here, I’ve plotted out four different “practice prescriptions”—sequences designed to help you reset, get grounded, quell your anxiety, and boost your energy. You’ll notice that we included some of the same poses in each sequence.….” my Practice RX series is up on @yogajournal 

For May, we are exploring 4 very different sequences that happen to all have the same (or quite similar) poses.

Observe how, by simply adjusting your intention, you can practice similar shapes and yet create totally different effects.

Check out the full series at my linktree or here https://www.yogajournal.com/practice/yoga-sequences/healing-yoga-poses/

Motherhood is both at once and everything in between. 

I used to think things had to be one way or the other. That there was a single answer for all things.

As a result of this black and white thinking, I would then experience enormous guilt for feeling anything even remotely “grey”.

But humans can feel two conflicting emotions at the same time. 

Mothers can absolutely LOVE their family and children and want a break.

It is yes/and rather than no/but. 

But I forget this all the time. Every day I’m torn between wanting things to slow down and wanting things to speed up. And then I’m plagued with guilt for not knowing what the right feeling is.

In that instance though, all my feelings are right and all my feelings are valid. They don’t cancel each other out.

We look at our kids and think, “Wow what complex, magical beings!”.

Well guess what…..you are too.

‘Kathryn Templeton is a highly accredited clinical psychologist, yoga therapist, and Ayurvedic practitioner based in Con- necticut. She is also the mother of three. 

Sleep is when the body and mind digest and repair. If we do not sleep enough, the body does not have the time and space to heal itself and we may get sick. 

Have you ever pulled an all- nighter for work or school and felt mild cold symptoms the next day? Well, multiply that by six months or more for new parents. 

Like the lines on a tree ring, you can always tell how many kids someone has by the number of bags under their eyes! 🐼 🐼 🐼 

Templeton calls following the sun’s lead “circadian medicine,” explaining, “When the sun rises, so do the birds and so should we. And when the sun sets, that’s when we should start to work toward our own sleep.” 

Something as simple as dimming the lights and choosing to read a book (ideally not on a tablet) before bed instead of watching television can profoundly a�ect that night’s sleep. 

Instead, what do most of us do at night? Keep the lights on long after the sun sets and watch a Netflix true crime documentary on a flickering screen…’ excerpted from The Yoga of Parenting.

Respect for all the moms of small children who are out in public WITHOUT your family.

We have all these self-sacrificing narratives of what a mom should and should not do.

When we see a mom out by herself (gasp) on a weekend (gasp!) or on Mother’s Day (double gasp!), there is often an assumption that the mom is being selfish.

How dare she abandon her family to meet her own needs? How dare she choose to spend her time doing anything else other than doting over her family? “It goes by so fast! You’ll miss this one day!”

It’s BS. 

First, moms need to do things for themselves and to be there own whole person, precisely so they can give to their families. You can’t pour from an empty cup.

Next, I assure you that no outing is ever done without lots of behind the scenes organization. Someone is crying, someone has lost something. There are often days of preparation leading up to a few hour excursion.

Last, it’s all done with a tinge of guilt. This whole, “you only get 18 summers” threat makes you feel as though you have to spend every waking moment with your kids, but if you are burnt out and resentful for a large portion of that time, is it truly quality?

Take care of yourself so you can take care of your family. 

Choose quality over quantity when it comes to time spent with your kids. 

And spend Mother’s Day however the heck YOU want. 

Moms: You are amazing 🙏🏼 What a fierce club we are all members of.  Our strength comes from abilities to nourish ourselves first.

That’s not selfish. That’s self preservation.

Launching a book is a crash course in vulnerability. 

Especially a book that has so many intimate personal stories…

I’ve been very surprised to find that, even though I am quite happy to talk about myself in written form, and even in short videos on social, I’m actually very uncomfortable when I’m being interviewed.

My brain is split between trying to answer thoughtfully, while also trying to read the interviewer’s reactions while also trying to foresee what people reading or listening later might think. 

 I often overshare in an attempt to appease my own nervousness which then makes me more nervous.

I much prefer being the one asking the questions .

I was on my way to do a talk on Wednesday night and completely in my head about all of this when I found a fortune cookie message on the floor of our car, which is interesting, considering that we haven’t been to Chinese food in months…

But it says “A warm heart guides others” and it reminded me that I’m not doing any of this for myself, alone.

I mean, let’s be real. Of course, I’m doing some of it for me! I love writing and I’ve always wanted to write a book, but the reason I love writing and the reason I wanted to write a book is because I love connecting with other people. I love helping people feel less alone.

One thing I think I will start doing is to stop talking about myself so much of these interviews and maybe start talking about all the amazing people that I interviewed for the book? 

Or I will just continue to overshare unapologetically and hope that someone will see themselves in me and feel a little bit less alone.

So if you ever think to yourself, “man, I am just full of sh*t right now” a) you’re not alone and b) be of service.

For a long time I equated magazine models with extreme thinness.

I grew up in the era of the super model. Cindy, Claudia, Christy. These fawns of women, standing 6 ft tall with legs taking up nearly all of that height. My one leg equivalent to their two.

My mum had been a model in the 60s and 70s. She would pull out her portfolio to show me ads she had been in—beehive hair and smoky eyes. She would diet relentlessly, giving me weight loss medication at 9yrs old.

When I started doing yoga, I swapped fashion mags for yoga publications. Lanky legs no longer walked on runways, they wrapped behind 📖people’s heads.

But unlike Vogue or Cosmo, the cover models on these mags were people I knew.  They were my teachers, my friends.  And all of them were extraordinarily beautiful and, let’s be honest, thin-framed.

I thought for sure when I became a mom and my body changed shape after pregnancy that any hope I had to be on a cover of anything would be dashed. Or at least tabled for the next however many years of breastfeeding and deep motherhood…

I had yet to see a postpartum body in any yoga magazine, let alone on the cover. 

But the time has come to stop hiding our motherhood and matrescence in the media and in yoga circles. 

My belly is soft because it stretched and grew with the womb that held my precious babies.

My muscles and ligaments and tendons are tighter from carrying and protecting my children.

My eyes have dark circles because I was up all night nourishing these little beings.

Thank you @yogamagazineofficial for sharing this mama at her realest= 6 month postpartum with two kids. 

And thank you @emilie.bers for always making me feel special and beautiful, no matter how tired I am.

How do you protect your sleep as a parent? 🤷🏻‍♀️This is not a riddle. 

Its actually what we do throughout the day that helps influence our night’s sleep. 

It’s called sleep hygiene and borrowing from Ayurveda, there are a few super simple things we can do today to help us sleep better tonight.

✅ Dim the lights
✅ Ditch (or limit) the screens 
✅ Wake up before dawn

I cover these and more in my book The Yoga of Parenting’s chapter on Ayurveda.

I interviewed the amazing @behappydoyoga Kathryn Templeton for the actual book and then I got to sit down with @ayurvedabysiva for my upcoming podcast, so I have lots of Ayurvedic wisdom and guidance to share with you all!

Ayurveda helps us be in better relationship with…well, everything!

Enjoy.

“When I think back to my teen years and early twenties, it boggles my mind that I was able to maintain the lifestyle I did. 

I moved fast, stayed up late, worked a high-intensity job in the film industry, lived on caffeine and cigarettes, and partied a lot. 

I was young and didn’t have kids. I was still a kid myself in a lot of ways, but when I got an ulcer, I knew it was time to make some adjustments. Or more accurately, my older sister told me I needed to.

Late one night, in a steamy room in Santa Monica, my sister, @jenrepo , took me to my first power yoga class. I had done asana many times up to that point, but it was mostly on video at home or in gym settings…

It was the best I had felt in years, and after just a few weeks attending of classes almost every day, I quickly became aware of the discordances between my old life and my desired new one….” Excerpted from The Yoga of Parenting in @layogamagazine !

@feliciatomasko launched my writing career in a lot of ways! She published my pieces before i knew what a byline was and always believed in me and my projects.

Parenting has been the messiest and most fulfilling part of my life. 

This week’s podcast guest, @sarahezrinyoga has written a beautiful new book that I wish I’d had when I first started this bumpy ride. 

In The Yoga of Parenting, Sarah holds  the space for us to be real about what it's like to attempt to be a mindful (and also sane! and boundaried!) parent in the modern age.
 
As yoga teachers or students, it's easy to be hard on ourselves, to feel like we should be more grounded, self-regulated, even peaceful (ha!) as parents.
 
Sarah clarifies early on (and then repeats it, because we need to hear it) throughout the book: We're perfectly imperfect. That's OK. From there she offers advice that is grounded and informed by yoga practice and philosophy.
 
Go listen to this episode for ideas about setting boundaries, creating community, and thoughts on "sharenting" and more.

Life lessons on the way to summer camp.

In the past 24hrs our commute has been detoured due to three different major car accidents on the 101.
Reminding me (and perhaps all of us?) to pump the brakes a bit. 

I live as if I’m flooring the gas pedal constantly, especially when it comes to my kids.

Jonah just had two weeks in between school ending and camp starting and admittedly I was wishing time would speed up so I could get him back into full time care.

But then this morn, as I was getting him ready for his first year of camp and having flashbacks of my own few summers at camp, and we come up on ambulances and fire tricks, the universe was all but screaming “pump the brakes!”.

Praying the families involved in the accidents are all okay, everyone looked okay, but considering how fast I can move, how distracted I can be, I will take these experiences as warning signs and reminders that summers with my kids is something to be savored, not rushed.

Even if we’re savoring it on the couch with Ninjago playing.

@diannebondyyogaofficial joins me on The Yoga of Parenting podcast this week 🎙️

My dad has been instrumental in creating some of the most iconic rock albums in history, but to me, he was just my dad, and the music was just loud….

The music was also the reason he was gone so much of the time.

My mother was absent a lot from my childhood, too, though hers was not a physical absence. 

No, she could be right next to you and her icy mood and alcohol-infused anger would make it feel as though she were miles away. 

I’ve never felt lonelier than sitting next to her at the breakfast table in the mornings before school…

I would prattle on nervously, while she sat hungover, rustling through her Los Angeles Times newspaper, a Dunhill menthol cigarette smoking in the ashtray beside us, covering up the smell of toast…

Despite the uncertainty and loneliness I experienced as a little girl, I wouldn’t trade a single second of my childhood…My family is currently the closest it has ever been…and every one of those seconds has led me to where I am now…

Every single second has also imparted some powerful lessons and gifts…”

Thank you @mariashriver @meghanrabbitt and @thesundaypaper for sharing my story in today’s edition.

We all grew up in some form of uncertainty because the very nature of life is change and movement. 

What tools do you use to anchor yourself and what gifts can you mine on the other side?

✅Raising resilient kids
✅Navigating important conversations about topics that can feel uncomfortable (i.e., s3x)

Gali has led a fascinating life. After serving in the Israeli Air forces, she traveled the world to find some peace of mind, and met her husband’s. 

She moved to the States in 2010 to study Psychology and Neuroscience and researched the effects of meditation and yoga on our mind and body, only to find that she no longer wanted to pursue an academic career. 

She traveled to India to practice and study, and became a certified yoga and meditation teacher. 

She founded Mini Yoga Club in 2014 which started as a yoga and mindfulness program in daycares and preschools around the Bay Area. 

When the pandemic hit, she became a mom for the first time, and turned Mini Yoga Club into an educational platform (mostly on IG) where she shares with parents how to practice yoga and meditation with their children in a fun, easy, quick, and playful way. 

Most recently she created 
The Yoga Play which is a screen-free, science-backed game that transforms the way parents and children connect, which is coming very soon.

The Yoga Play Kit combines the power of yoga, mindfulness, breathing exercises, music, pretend play, and social-emotional skills, to equip parents and children with proven tools to reduce stress and enhance physical, mental, and emotional well-being.

Join us tomorrow Thurs 7/6, 1030a PT

Controversial opinion: My kids learn a lot more about me, themselves, and the world when I get angry and repair with them than if I never allow them see me get angry. 

Now, I’m not encouraging that we lead with anger. But if you get short or raise your voice, it’s an opportunity for healing and learning that is worth WAY more than if you’ve never shown them irritation or anger or frustration.

Parents, you’re a human being! Humans have a wide range of emotions and though the jury is still out about anger being a primary or secondary emotion, it’s still considered an emotion and it’s still something we will likely experience around parenthood at some point.

Kids can be triggering. Some feel like they’re put on this planet specifically to test us (karmically this might be true!). 

It’s not about never getting upset. 

It’s what you do with it on the other side. 

How do you choose to regulate yourself when you are dysregulated? How do you repair if you weren’t able to catch yourself in time? What are you modeling to your kids?

What do you think?👇🏼👇🏼👇🏼

“My preschooler fell 15 feet off of a play structure last week.

He was pouring blood from the back of his head and we were unsure if he had broken his neck or cracked his skull. 

He told me the world was spinning and though I wasn’t the one who fell, I felt the same way…

He left the hospital with only a single staple in the back of his head and before we even made it to the car, started running and asking about the fair we were due to attend the following day…

We went to the fair the following day (as we had promised him [and the doctor okay’ed]) and he played games and rode rides and ate funnel cake as though he hadn’t been in a neck brace less than 24 hours prior. 

Meanwhile, I found myself looking around and wondering if I was supposed to be doing the same….

…even with my decades long yoga practice and awareness of the nervous system, I have moments of thinking, “I should just be over it by now, right?”. 

I wonder how other people would have done it. Should we have been in “mourning” and not left the house the entire following week? Should I have been smiling and riding the rides and in the moment?

What should I be doing? What would THEY do? What’s the right way?…”

Do you ever have those days where you just want to crawl out of your own skin?🙋🏻‍♀️

I was ensconced in discomfort yesterday, and I figured out that it was because I was in an “I want” state.

And mostly wanting things that would have taken me out of the present moment, where I was uncomfortable.

Yesterday, I paused, and instead of avoiding the discomfort, I sat and asked myself “what am I feeling? “

I practiced being in the state of I AM, even though the “I am” answer at the moment was, “ I am uncomfortable.”

The next time you’re feeling like you want to crawl out of your own skin, I invite you to pause in everything you’re feeling instead. 

You may find yourself feeling more comfortable more quickly.

Postpartum hormones have me OVERHEATING this summer.
Check out this cooling practice from @diva_transcending 
・・・
Getting overheated can not just be in your body, but in your mind, too. Reset your nervous system by regulating Triple Heater meridian.
 
According to TCM (Traditional Chinese Medicine), there are energetic lines in the body that correlate to a variety of emotions. We’re playing with this theory in our approach to the postures in Yin Yoga. The line known as Triple Warmer/Triple Heater/San Jiao meridian correlates to our fight, flight, and freeze responses. Giving it a reset is a great way to cool down, whether it’s your body or your mind, this summer or whenever you need it.

Try this check in before practicing:
Notice what you sense in the body, observe your breath, name any emotions or thoughts. 

Then do the practice a little slower with the cadence of your own breath.

Repeat the check in and observe differences with nonattachment and compassion. 

Let me know how it went below! ⬇️

70-100% of new moms experience intrusive thoughts, according to a 2019 study from BMC Psychiatry.

Intrusive thoughts are unwanted thoughts and images that tend to be of a v10l3nt or s3xua1 nature. 

They can involve picturing horrific things happening to you and your kids and even imagining yourself doing some of those things.

They are scary and intrusive (as their name implies), but they are also TOTALLY NORMAL! Especially for new parents (most studies looked at moms but I know many dads who get them to).

My theory is that much of it’s survival. We picture the absolute worst scenarios so we know how we can protect our kids.

Of course some intrusive thoughts might be an indication of more severe mental health disorders like postpartum OCD or psychosis.

This is why you must stay in touch with a provider (doc, midwife, therapist) who you trust.

And if they’re “normal intrusive thoughts” (not an oxymoron), YOGA CAN HELP!

Yoga teaches us how to choose our thoughts. And it frickin’ works!

Here’s how:
✅ ID the scary thought and label it as such “this is an ‘intrusive thought’”
✅ ID something happening in present reality.
✅ start to repeat THAT like a mantra 

Even if you have to spend all day lassoing your thoughts back to reality it is well worth it!!!

Deep breaths. You’re doing great.

It’s @wanderlust__tv Wed! #wltvwed which means a new week and session of our Yoga of Parenting special series!

This week, we’re getting to know our nervous system.

A healthy nervous system swings like a pendulum between our sympathetic nervous system, which is our activated state (often called fight or fight) and our parasympathetic nervous system response, known rest and digest. 

We don’t only need the sympathetic nervous system to save our babies from danger, we need it to run around the backyard with them. Even to simply get out of bed! The challenge is when we’re locked in a chronic stress response. In this flow class, we will explore a variety of balance shapes and inversions, so we can get familiar with our nervous system and learn how to settle it more readily. 

Through movement, we will identify what our body does when we are heightened and what it needs to calm down.

This week we explore the concept of tapas, purification through heat. 

Parenting is intense, between the early days of nonstop crying and toddler meltdowns to the uncomfortable stresses of raising a teen in today’s world. 

Long holds and strong poses give us an opportunity to practice being present in intensity. 

Our impulse is often to avoid or dull discomfort, but whenever we do that we end up dulling the good right along with the uncomfortable. The better we can learn to be fully present in every moment, the sweeter and more rewarding the sweet moments. 

Think of how powerful their smile is after you work to soothe your baby. Or how moving your adult child’s hug is after a misunderstanding. 

This class teaches us how to embrace intensity for our growth and gain.

“Prenatal yoga classes are all about preparing the body for expansion. But what about the coming back together that is necessary after giving birth?

The pelvic region undergoes significant changes from pregnancy to birth. 

From conception to full term, the pelvis expands to accommodate the growing uterus and, eventually, a baby. The pelvic bowl also changes shape multiple times during the labor process alone…

Just as yoga can help prepare the body for birthing a new life, it can also help restore it afterward. Just keep in mind that the pieces may fit a little differently...” from my new @yogajournal article “5 Postnatal Yoga Poses to Improve Pelvic Stability”

When I had my first son, I had a really hard time finding postnatal workouts that weren’t perpetuating diet culture or the get your body back myth. I was especially disappointed at the lack of resources in the yoga world.

Almost 4yrs later, I’m very happy to report there has been a huge movement toward mindful postpartum recovery in fitness.

I got to speak to some of those Trail Blazers, including  @ruthhealthco ‘s @kimberlymcferron @vibrantmamawellness and @the.yogini.nancy

There’s always an opportunity to pause when traveling with young kids. 

It may not be long, and you may not get many of them, but when you start to pay attention, you will start to find blips of calm even in the most chaotic moments. 

Running late to the airport? When you arrive and you’re in line for security: pause and breathe.

Difficulties getting on the plane without a meltdown? The second they’re all set in their seat and you sit in yours, pause and breathe.

Does it feel like a cattle call getting off the plane and finding baggage claim? Breathe deeply while you wait for your bags and the kids are contained in strollers. 

Meditation doesn’t have to happen alone in a cave away from the world. 

The most advanced practices are the ones we do IN the world. 

And parents are advanced practitioners….especially when traveling with young kids!

Our kids don’t always listen to us, but I can guarantee you they are watching.

As someone who is highly sensitive and an introvert, I often need a lot of downtime after being around other people.

My eldest is very similar. He needs a ton of recovery time after a lot of social interaction. Naturally, the universe came him a bro that is NONstop and all up in your business.

Ive been so impressed how well my son can communicate when he needs space! Whether it’s asking to eat breakfast alone in his room or to “sit in silence” in the car, he’s able to articulate his needs.

I don’t take credit for much in parenting.
I truly believe these souls come here with their own karma and paths, but I’d like to think that my modeling needing and taking breaks has been part of the what taught him.

Or maybe he’s here to teach me?

Recorded at my Yoga of Parenting book event with @tarastiles at @athleta Sept ‘23.

I haven’t used the phrase “my love cup is full” in a long time. 

I would spend time with a friend for coffee, or get to partake in a training as a student, or even get to lead a training as the teacher, and I would leave feeling FULL. 

Full where though? And with what?

I couldn’t really describe what I meant by that word. It’s just that the hole I so often walk around with—the deep seated feelings of inadequacy and unlovability—would disappear for a while.

I wouldn’t need all the external things I normally grasp to, like success, or status, to feel defined. I was/am just love. 

After last night’s Yoga of Parenting event with @mental_health_yoga @saragallagherbloom at @morphobleu.studio , my cup runneth over!!!! I’m beyond full with love and community.

@saragallagherbloom and I were talking before the event about how many people feel completely stripped down. Like they have zero resilience. 

Her theory is that part of what is missing is community and love. That without their cup filled, they are raw and empty. 

Well, I can speak for myself when I say, I am a totally different person having done all of these amazing events with such amazing people. Being in circle reminded me that I ACHE for community and collective learning. 

And I’m sooo grateful to Sara and Melanie for hosting me and the beautiful MTL @happytreeyoga and Morpho Bleu yoga community for welcoming me so lovingly.

Love cup FILLED🫶🏻🫶🏻🫶🏻🫶🏻🫶🏻

When I was 12, my parents punished me for “out of control “ behavior by taking away a modeling opportunity because they said I clearly couldn’t handle the excitement.

I never wanted to miss an opportunity like that again, so I learned how to bottle up my excitement and use it like jet fuel to propel my way up a hill.

What I often forget is that you need to save some energy to come down the other side of the mountain.

Come downs are so uncomfortable for me. I convince myself it will always be this way.

I will always feel this way. 

I forget that we need the comedown. It’s a natural and necessary part of life cycles. The tide ebbs and the moon wanes after it waxes.

My tank is empty right now and instead of forcing myself forward I’m just going to lie down.

Oof we are entering a new phase of parenting that is requiring alllll my presence and grounding…and my kids didn’t even do anything.

The new phase? Friendships and peer relations. 

I knew our old stuff comes up in parenting (I mean I wrote a whole book about it) but I was blindsided by how affected I’d be.

When I see my son being turned down or ignored it’s like a punch to the gut. 

I want to jump in and save him. I want to hug him and yell, “They’re loss.”

I want to tell those little kids that they’re missing out on hanging with a very special little boy.

What I really want to do is climb back into the past and all the times I was rejected by peers and hold myself as a little girl. 

But this isn’t what’s happening in the present.
It’s not life or my story. It’s his. My job as his mom is  not to manipulate and force. It’s to comfort him IF he needs me. 

My yoga practice right now doesn’t involve poses. It is taking a deep breath when I’m triggered in motherhood so I can show up wholly for my kids.

Parenting is yoga.

Bryana Kappadakunnel is an LMFT specializing in Infant-Family Early Childhood Mental Health, Perinatal Mental Health, and a Certified Conscious Parenting Coach via @doctorshefali training program. 

She is the creator of the online community Conscious Mommy where she teaches parents to become the conscious parent they never had. 

For over a decade, Bryana has worked exclusively with families with very young children to navigate challenges related to child development, behavioral & emotional issues, attachment problems, and trauma. 

Her work is influenced by attachment theory and the neurorelational framework. 

Even though she is a family therapist, she works primarily with parents by helping them discover their child’s nervous system and developmental needs. In this process, parents also learn how to regulate their own triggered reactions and discover more self-control and self-compassion. 

She also guides parents to develop vital skills in self-reflection & deconstructing familial cycles of guilt and shame, which aims to drastically shift the child-parent relational patterns.

Bryana also works with new moms experiencing perinatal mood or anxiety disorders. 

She uses a conscious- and mindfulness-informed approach to help moms realign their expectations with reality, deconstruct the guilt & shame they’re experiencing, and shift into the present moment, where depression and anxiety cannot exist.

On top of all this, she is the mom of 2 young children, and lives with her spouse in Southern California.

Bryana’s teachings and content have been a guide post to me and I’m thrilled to get to know her even better.

I was deeply enmeshed with my mum. 

She was my everything and when I lost her, I didn’t know what to do with myself. 

My feelings became even more complicated when I became a mom myself. 

I found myself reconciling with the pain of growing up with an alcoholic mother, who was often distant,
angry and cold. But I also know she loved me deeply. I know I made her laugh. I know I was a light for her darkness.

I also now know that what I interpreted as coldness was really just her own unbearable anxiety…and I witness myself shutting down or distancing with my own kids and find a voice from within crying, “Not this time.”

But who’s to say she didn’t do the same? Who’s to say that part of her anxiety was because she was trying to stop eons of ancestral alcoholism and abuse.

It’s exhausting being a cycle breaker but I realize now that im not just breaking the cycles because her, I am breaking these cycles BECAUSE OF her 🙏🏼

“I’m feeling both flooded and drained,” my Jewish neighbor texted me a few days ago. 

It hit the nail on the head for me and I realized that I had been allowing myself to be swept to sea and emptied out over and over. 

I was missing the vital practice of discernment. Discernment is a super power.

Truly. It’s only possible because of the neocortex higher brain. When we’re reactive and emotional and operating from survival, we’re in the lower parts of our brain. Our mammalian limbic system and our reptilian brain stem.

Discernment is what makes us human and separates us from other animals. It’s what enables us to have agency.

Yes, I’m flooded and drained because of the news cycle and the horrors happening, but I’m making choices that feed into those experiences. I’m reading every story and watching every vid.

But I don’t have to . YOU don’t have to. Discernment is wisdom.

Being a human being is nuanced and complex and rich and powerful precisely because we can discern.

That’s my word for the week and my suggestion for all of you.

When you’re feeling flooded and/or drained, discern. What choices are you making? What can you control?

Take care of your hearts.

“Traveling with young children is not for the faint of heart. 

Traveling solo is stressful enough with its ever-changing timetables, luggage lugging and unfamiliar territory. 

Add in some hangry, crying kids, and suddenly your vacation from work becomes work. 

One way to reap the benefits of travel without incurring as many stressors is with a classic staycation…” my recent article on @mother.ly explores 5 Reasons to Stay Local your next fam vacation.

Are you operating from your small self (fear-based, reactive) or your higher Self?

The socials are a really toxic place right now, but I keep signing in. I keep reading comments sections. I keep pinballing back and forth between emotions . 

When I get into this phase, I try to remind myself, “this is your small self, Sarah”.

Because this isn’t my true Self. No, no:  there is a part of me (a part of all of us) that exists beyond this earthly realm where we seem ruled by ego and fear. 

A part of us that connects us not only to something bigger, but each other. 

We’re all sparks of the same star.

Drops in the same ocean.
 
Whenever I’m catching myself rounded around my phone, literally making myself smaller, I take a deep breath and remind myself- this is your small self.

I put my hand on my heart or I touch one of my kids. I tap into the bright unconditional light and love we’re ALL born with (though the muck of generational trauma and conditioning can make it seem dim).

I try to tap into my higher Self- the part of me that is you and the part of you that is me.

It’s from this place I want to live my life. It’s from this place I want to live in the world. It’s from this place I can find peace. And so can you.

I ask you to check in right now: are you hunched over your device, fueled by fear, and making yourself small????

Put the phone down, sit up tall, place your hand your heart and remind yourself: I AM LOVE. WE ARE ALL LOVE.

Sending you all love.

One of the great thrills of writing a book is seeing it on the shelf in a store! Or at least that’s what my author friends tell me…

Bc I’ve gone into multiple bookstores around the world and only one has had my book so far and my friend (fellow author @jjelliott There Are No Rules for This) bought it before I saw it on the shelf. 
 
WELL all that changed today when I went @copperfieldsbooks at the Marin country mart and saw my book in the wild! 

Actually, more accurately, I wrote the person who does the buying for the store and begged them to carry, it explaining I’m a local author, but STILL…it was there!!!! 

I not only signed it, I got to see it on the shelf in all its glory!

I just want to share this because I think it’s important to know all sides of the author journey.

People post about their global book tours and sold out author events, but not about the fact that we sometimes have to beg a place to carry our book at all.

Still, I wouldn’t trade this for anything. The Yoga of Parenting is my third baby and I will continue to fight for its rightful place in the world with all I got!!!!!

Feeling so helpless, and uncomfortably privileged these days, but I have to keep reminding myself that showing up as a kind human every day is a form of activism.

Here are 3 things you can do RIGHT NOW that will change the world:
1. BREATHE: we are social creatures who use another to co-regulate. Notice your breathing and try to slow it down. The people near you will unconsciously do the same.

2. SMILE: listen don’t fake it by any means, but if you see another human out in the world and you feel safe, consider smiling. It signals safety back to them.

3. COMPLIMENTS: It feels good to be seen and appreciated. Pick someone in your outer circle or a stranger to be kind to.

Kindness is activism.

Taking care of your heart IS saving the world.

REMINDER🔔: Self-care IS NOT selfish

We must take care of ourselves to fill our own cup so we can then pour into those we love.

My oldest is home today for Veteran’s Day and I could’ve skipped my mindful movement practice today to spend more time with him according to the clock, but you know what???!! The quality of that time would be 👎🏻👎🏻👎🏻👎🏻👎🏻 

Instead, I opted to put him on a screen and prioritize doing @theclass for 1 hour. 

On paper that may have looked like one less hour together, but the quality of my attention after I finished was EXPONENTIALLY sharper than if I’d skipped it. 

Taking that time away from him (aka FOR ME) allowed me to give him more time because now I am able to be that much more present.

This is the yoga of parenting.
